shared_text:
Faribault High School
September 13 at 3:35 PM ·

**NEW STAFF SPOTLIGHT**

Name: Grace Simpson

Hometown: Menomonie, WI

Role at FHS: Choir Director

Faribault High School is excited to welcome Grace Simpson as our new Choir Director. Grace earned her degree in Music Education from Luther College and before coming to FHS she served as a Dorian Summer Music Camp Counselor. “I’m excited to work in such a supportive and caring community”, said Simpson when asked what she looked forward to the most about working in Faribault.

When she’s not serving students, Grace loves to read, do yoga, pet dogs, and drink too much coffee! She also loves this quote from Eleanor Roosevelt: “The future belongs to those who believe in the beauty of their dreams”. Grace feels that we should dream boldly about the things in life we find to be beautiful. And when we dream beautifully, the future is ours.

Please join Faribault Public Schools in welcoming Grace Simpson into our Falcon Family!

The Minnesota Department of Education has announced an extension of the Summer Food Service Program, which means all students in Faribault Public Schools will receive free breakfast and lunch to start the school year.

This does not change plans for how breakfast and lunch will be served at each building. Distance learning students can still pick up meals at their schools, but you no longer have to call ahead to the office. A food service employee will hand out meals from 9:30-10 a.m. daily at the main entrance at each school.

We ask that all families fill out the free/reduced lunch form so your eligibility status will be correct once this program expires: https://www.faribault.k12.mn.us/departments/food-and-nutrition

Lunch fees will be charged according to student eligibility status. Attached is the distance learning menu for September.

Faribault has seen a reduction in pollution since the installation of solar gardens last fall, and the school district has seen another reduction — in its energy bill.

To date, Faribault Public Schools Financial Director Andrew Adams said the district saved approximately $11,300 on energy costs since March. Nokomis Energy, the solar garden provider for the district, expects another $17,000 in savings between now and December. Annually, the district could save between $24,000 and $30,000.

https://www.southernminn.com/faribault_daily_news/news/article_9039d11a-aa1d-5ab2-ab0f-372a73503b90.html

post_text:
This spring, over 300 students, parents, staff and community members attended our strategic planning sessions to help us establish the priorities of our school district.

The first stage of that process was completed Monday night when the school board approved our new mission statement and our five strategies for supporting our mission.

The next stage of the planning process will come when our administration presents its action steps for addressing each of our five strategies; Student-centered learning, Equity, Mental Health and Safety, School Climate and Family and Community Engagement.

Thank you to everyone who participated in our strategic planning process. You helped us build a framework for a strategic plan that will guide our district for years to come.

https://www.faribault.k12.mn.us/district/vision-and-mission

shared_text:
Faribault High School
July 10 at 7:26 AM ·

Faribault High School Assistant Principal, Joe Sage has received a "Star of Innovation" award for his excellent leadership on THE NEST project. The award is designed to recognize school leaders around the state of Minnesota for the development and support of an exemplary and innovative education program in their school. As part of the recognition, Mr. Sage received $100, which will go toward future projects in THE NEST. Mr. Sage's work to bring THE NEST to life has allowed free access to clothing, toiletries, school supplies, dental services, and mental health support to students. Well done, Joe! Our students and community thank you for your efforts.

post_text:
Hello everyone,

After much thought and feedback from families and the coordination team, we have decided to forgo this year's Summer STEAM program. Families expressed deep concern about being able to have their children persist in distance learning over the summer. We have to respect their wishes and start planning for the 2020-2021 school year and 2021 Summer STEAM!

A huge thank you to everyone who was part of the recruitment process and those who were ready to teach in July. If there are alternate opportunities to move any type of targeted services programming forward this summer, we will let you know.

Thank you,

~The STEAM Team

The Faribault School District’s English Learner program has had its share of successes this past academic year, as seen in achievements of its students.

According to Sam Ouk, multilingual and equity coordinator for Faribault schools, a record 70 secondary students achieved English proficiency requirements this year in the district. Many EL students are exiting the program faster than the the five- to seven-year expectation as well, instead exiting in two to three years.

Thank you to all the students, parents, staff and community members who participated in our strategic planning survey. Big River Group has continued the strategic planning process this week by meeting online with our staff.

Next week's Zoom meetings will be specifically for students, parents and other community members. Everyone is invited to participate in one of these meetings, which will last about 75 minutes. In the meetings, Big River Group will review the results of the survey, facilitate small-group discussions and provide an opportunity for feedback about what the district's strategic plan should entail. This includes input on the mission, vision and goals of the district.

post_text: Sam Ouk, our district Equity and Multilingual Program Coordinator, recently shared his story with the Minnesota Humanities Center. We're happy to have Sam on our team, working to help us eliminate barriers for our students.
shared_text:
MNHUM.ORG
Cambodian Minnesotan Stories: Sam Ouk

Minnesota Humanities Center
May 13 at 1:00 PM ·

In celebrating the 45th Anniversary of the Asian Diaspora, the Council on Asian Pacific Minnesotans and the Minnesota Humanities Center have collaborated on this story telling project which features Cambodian Minnesotan communities leaders during the 2020 Asian Pacific Heritage Month.

Today we feature Sam Ouk, Equity and Multilingual Program Coordinator for Fairbault Public Schools. Committed to meeting the needs of his students and their families, Sam works to eliminate language, resource, and technological barriers.

Sam stresses the importance of "...understanding where you came from, who you are, and how that plays into each and every decision you make." Thank you, Sam, for choosing to break barriers and empower immigrant and refugee communities and for sharing your story with us!

Dear Faribault Public Schools community,

As announced yesterday, Governor Tim Walz and the Minnesota Department of Education have extended distance learning through the remainder of the school year. The governor has set aside Friday, May 1st and Monday, May 4th as days for staff to prepare for this next phase of distance learning.

This means that May 1st and May 4th will be professional development days for our staff. As a result, students will not be required to attend school via distance learning on these days.

The district will continue to provide child care for tier one and tier two workers and free meals on those days. Go to our website for more details.

Thank you for your cooperation and understanding as we continue distance learning through the end of this school year. We are Faribault and we will get through this together.

Superintendent Todd Sesker

Yesterday our school district resumed our strategic planning process. We will spend the next two weeks gathering additional information through surveys that have been sent out to students, parents, staff and community members.

All this input is being collected so we can develop a strategic plan that reflects our community’s vision for the school district and outlines how the district can continue to best-serve our community’s learners. We hope you can join us online for our strategic planning community meetings May 18-19 where we will review and discuss the results of the survey and continue to establish priorities and goals for the district.

Thank you for helping us chart a course for a successful future for our school district!

We hope you can join us online for our strategic planning community meetings May 18-19 where we will review and discuss the results of the survey and continue to establish priorities and goals for the district.

Thank you for helping us chart a course for a successful future for our school district!

Click here to participate in our strategic planning survey:

http://survey.constantcontact.com/survey/a07egw2u6w1k619k1ta/a025j0k9cwb4wn/questions

Beginning on Thursday, April 23, free food boxes will be available each Thursday and Friday to all Faribault residents. There are no age restrictions on these food boxes.

This program will be run in partnership with Faribault Public Schools’ student food service program.

On Thursdays, a Hiawathaland bus will distribute food boxes from 10 a.m. to noon at Cannon River Mobile Home Park, McKinley Early Childhood Center and Sunrise Mobile Home Park. Deliveries will be dropped off at Chester Ct. Circle near Roberds Lake between 9:30 a.m. and 10 a.m.

On Fridays, the buses will distribute food boxes from 10 a.m. to noon at Four Seasons Apartments and Buckham Library. A bus will stop at Evergreen Estates Mobile Home Park from 10 a.m.-10:50 a.m. and Knollwood Mobile Home Park from 11 a.m.-noon.

The food is provided through a grant from the Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Minnesota Foundation. Growing up Healthy, Faribault Youth Investment, Faribault Community School, the YMCA, and Hiawathaland Transit are partnering to support this free service.

Faribault Public Schools is looking for volunteers to sew masks for our child care workers and food service staff and volunteers. To put together the masks, you will need the following sewing supplies: a sewing machine, 100 percent cotton fabric (pre-shrunk), thread, scissors, pins, and an iron and ironing board.

If you don’t have fabric, you can pick it up at Faribault High School from 8-10 a.m. on Monday, April 13. Masks can be dropped off in a receptacle at Roosevelt Elementary Door 2 daily between 8 a.m. and 3 p.m.

Here are the JOANN Fabric instructions for making the masks:

https://www.joann.com/on/demandware.static/-/Library-Sites-LibraryJoAnnShared/default/dw4148ae36/static/landingpage/assets/MaskInstructions_V2.pdf

If you have questions while putting the masks together,contact FACS teacher Kaylee Wiens at kwiens@faribault.k12.mn.us.

Your help is greatly appreciated as we do everything we can to keep our staff and volunteers healthy.

post_text:
Roosevelt Elementary fourth-graders share their thoughts on distance learning. Together we will all continue to learn and grow through this process!

"I think that distance learning is cool. My favorite part of the first week is I learned new things every day. the trickiest part was the assignments that told me to take a picture because it wouldn’t let me use my tablet to take a picture (because it only has a front camera) and I had to use my moms iPad."

"I felt kinda sad and happy because I don't get to see my teacher and friends but happy because I get to see my family.
I like you can do it any time in the day. it was tricky to learn."

"I liked that there are no interruptions and I can listen to music while I work. What was tricky is it's hard to sit and look at a screen when i'm trying to learn. I felt really good that I made it through doing a good job."

Faribault Middle School
April 6 at 8:45 AM ·

A distance learning story from a proud FMS teacher:

"I have a young man who is stuck in Mexico because of covid-19 for at least another month and is technically a drop. He missed us so much that he joined our Google Meets that I had invited him to; all the way, live and in color, from Michoacan, Mexico! He asked if he could continue to join us and hang out with us. That is so awesome my eyes welled up. That young man showed me that through all the challenges of distance learning, there are some bright spots. BIG shout out goes to that young man and his family!!!! Can I have an Amen brother!"

In an effort to continue to best-serve our Faribault Public Schools families, we are making adjustments to our breakfast and lunch meal delivery plan.

Beginning next week, we will distribute meals at three additional locations: McKinley Early Childhood Center, Discovery School and the Faribault Education Center.

We are also moving the pick-up time from 7-9 a.m. to 10 a.m. to noon. Students and parents/guardians can pick up FREE meals from any of our seven bus locations during that time.

Anyone who preferred the earlier pick-up time can stop at the FEC. That site will be open from 7-noon.

Faribault Public Schools will be closed Monday, March 16, and remain closed through March 27 to combat the spread of COVID-19 (coronavirus). We will continue to develop our response based on the recommendations of the Minnesota Department of Health, Governor Walz, and the Minnesota Department of Education.

We will not activate flexible learning days during this time. We will use this time to plan for longer-term distance learning needs should the state extend the closure beyond March 27.

We are dedicated to ensuring the health and safety of our students as we continue to navigate this public health crisis.

Click here for more information: https://faribault.k12.mn.us/cms/One.aspx?portalId=3060799&pageId=69482875

Congratulations to assistant principal Joe Sage, a winner of Minnesota Campus Compact's 2020 Presidents' Engaged Campus Award for his commitment to civic responsibility and community leadership!

“It is an absolute honor to be recognized for this work,” Sage said. “I appreciate the collaboration between our community partners, specifically Carleton College, and Faribault Public Schools staff. Together, we have been engaging in some very powerful and impactful work around equity, which has allowed us to give more of a voice to our Latinx and Somali families. We’ve been fortunate to have so many families willing to partner with our schools to help us improve academic success for all students.”

Our school district has begun the process of developing a new strategic plan. We need your help to develop a strategic plan that reflects our community’s vision for the school district and outlines how the district can continue to best-serve the community’s learners. The three things you can do to make your voice heard are:

1. Go to our website to stay updated on the strategic planning process: https://www.faribault.k12.mn.us/district/StrategicPlanning2020

2. Take this brief survey to let us know what you would and wouldn't change about our district: http://survey.constantcontact.com/survey/a07egw2u6w1k619k1ta/start

3. Join strategic planning moderator Bruce Miles April 13 from 6:30-8:30 p.m. at the Faribault High School cafeteria to help formulate the mission, vision and goals of our district. Free dinner will be served beginning at 5:30 p.m. and free child care will be provided.

Thank you for helping us chart a path for a successful future for Faribault Public Schools!

post_text:
Good luck today to our Director of Community Education Anne Marie Leland as she defends her dissertation, her final step toward earning her doctorate in educational leadership from Minnesota State University-Moorhead!

Anne Marie began the doctoral program in 2017. Her dissertation, entitled Full-Service Community School Intervention: Case Study of Somali Parent-School Engagement within a Rural Midwestern School District, has practical applications that will inform the way Faribault Public Schools approaches parent engagement moving forward.

Anne Marie thanks everyone who participated in her research and training, the district for the support and encouragement she has received while pursuing her doctorate, and school board member Jason Engbrecht, who has volunteered to serve on her dissertation defense committee. She said the opportunity to conduct her research has been the pinnacle of her 25 years in education and workforce development.

Good luck, Anne Marie!

Good luck today to our Director of Community Education Anne Marie Leland as she defends her dissertation, her final step toward earning her doctorate in educational leadership from Minnesota State University-Moorhead!

Anne Marie began the doctoral program in 2017. Her dissertation, entitled Full-Service Community School Intervention: Case Study of Somali Parent-School Engagement within a Rural Midwestern School District, has practical applications that will inform the way Faribault Public Schools approaches parent engagement moving forward.

Anne Marie thanks everyone who participated in her research and training, the district for the support and encouragement she has received while pursuing her doctorate, and school board member Jason Engbrecht, who has volunteered to serve on her dissertation defense committee. She said the opportunity to conduct her research has been the pinnacle of her 25 years in education and workforce development.

Good luck, Anne Marie!

"I feel lucky to have grown up in Faribault, and one reason is that I was able to try all kinds of different classes, sports and activities—including many I wasn’t good at! I realized at an early age it’s ok to not excel at everything you try, and that there’s a lot to learn from failure. I also learned the importance of character. Our teachers and coaches modeled and expected kindness, respect, teamwork, discipline—attributes that are crucial no matter your career path—and I’m grateful those lessons were part of my education." -alum Janel Klein

Read more from Janel in the February Around 656 newsletter: https://www.smore.com/tkahr-around-656

Roosevelt Elementary School
February 7 at 2:49 PM ·

Finalists have been chosen from all three Faribault Elementary Schools for the 10th Annual Sodexo Future Chefs Culinary Competition. Congratulations to these 3 Roosevelt students: Gabriella M (4-1), Ruth C (2-3) and Ainsley L (4-1)!!
Each contestant submitted a recipe for the theme, "Reimagine Your Favorite School Lunch Menu" and will be preparing this recipe at the contest on March 4th at the Faribault High School.
Finalists will be judged on taste, originality, ease of preparation, kid appeal, healthy attributes, use of featured ingredients, presentation of their sample plate and their verbal presentation as a Student Chef.
Sodexo will be presenting lots of prizes and the Grand Prize winner will also be entered into the National Competition!

Good Luck to our three Roosevelt Rockets!

Warmington got in touch with business teacher and DECA advisor Jared Kegler and signed up for the game in early November. By the time the online game wrapped up on Dec. 13, Warmington had turned his virtual $100,000 into over $116,000.

As we begin what Governor Walz recently proclaimed Paraprofessional Recognition Week, I want to send a special thank you to the over 100 paraprofessionals who play integral roles in the success of our students at schools throughout District 656.

We count on you to fill a wide variety of roles to make our schools run smoothly and you always rise to the occasion. As classroom paras, early childhood paras, ELL paras, special education paras, interpreters, cultural liaisons, educational assistants, and nurses, you provide incredible support for our students and teachers and we are grateful for your efforts. Thank you for all you do to make our schools successful!

Every day this week we will feature one of our paras so you can learn more about them and their contributions to our schools.

Todd S.

post_text:
On Monday, Faribault Public Schools, the Faribault Diversity Coalition and the Virtues Project will host the sixth-annual Martin Luther King Jr. Breakfast at South Central College. FHS students and Kymn Anderson from the Virtues Project will deliver a keynote address based on the virtues of MLK's I have a Dream speech: love, friendliness and unity.

A breakfast with a multicultural menu will be served from 8-10 a.m. There will be an interfaith invocation, FHS choir students will perform songs from the civil rights era and winners of the high school, middle school and elementary poetry contest will read their poems. Discussions about justice and equity will follow from 10-11 a.m.

The entire community is invited to attend.

“My involvement in the arts, athletics, and academics has allowed me to have experiences and has given me opportunities that I wouldn't have had otherwise. These experiences have allowed me to connect with older generations who’ve mentored me, as well as with younger generations whom I’ve mentored. I’ve learned that it’s not talent that allows certain people to succeed, it’s their work ethic and determination to achieve their goals. Whether that was studying for a test, practicing for a concert, or a high pressure match, preparing myself beforehand is a life skill that I’ve learned early because of my involvement in high school.”

-Senior Erica Johnsrud

Faribault High School

Congratulations to Abdi Abdullahi! This past weekend, Abdi was awarded his Masters Degree in Educational Leadership from the Minnesota State University, Mankato.

Abdi has worked at Faribault High School for 3 years as our Somali Cultural Liaison and is an integral member of our team. He does so much every day for our school, our students, and our community. We are so proud of him and his accomplishments! Please join us in congratulating Abdi on his outstanding achievement.
